FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE - RUSSIA (06): (VLADIMIR) BOVINE, SEROTYPE ASIA 1, DAIRY PRODUCTS RECALL, INTERNATIONAL IMPACT
*********************************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this update:
[1] Putin advocates transparency; international trade impact
[2] Transparency, dairy products recall

******
[1] Putin advocates transparency; international trade impact
Date: Fri 28 Oct 2016
Source: Russiskaya Gazeta [in Russian, machine trans. edited]
http://tinyurl.com/jdntzky


"All activities applied in combating FMD in the Vladimir region should be transparent; comprehensive information should be provided in the country and abroad," President Vladimir Putin said at a meeting with rice producers in Sochi. He also requested support for the victims [animal owners].

"You have good people working on the matter; I do not doubt their qualifications. The only thing that I would like to ask is that nothing be hidden; the work should be transparent, clear in our country. Our partners must know the full details of what is happening and what steps we have undertaken in order to arrest these threats, in order to have the confidence of our partners."

Agriculture Minister Alexander Tkachev said that the work is "open" from the 1st day. "We are well aware that it is impossible to hide it," he said. "Most important is to confine and isolate the outbreak," the official said. "For us, it is a big blow, because as you know, we have been globally recognized just 6 months ago as a country free of FMD. For us, this disease problem is of course of fundamental importance, if we are talking about exporting to China and other countries," Tkachev said. "And everyone who has somehow suffered should be helped," concluded Mr. Putin.

The outbreak of FMD in the Vladimir region became known on 20 Oct 2016. The village is under quarantine. The livestock in the region has been vaccinated. This is the 1st outbreak of FMD in the region since 1993.

[Byline: Kira Latukhina]

